        üìö <h2>The Content</h2>
        <div class="section">
            <h3>CIA Triad Basics</h3>
            <p>The foundation of cybersecurity: <span class="emphasis">Confidentiality</span> (keep secrets secret), <span class="emphasis">Integrity</span> (data stays accurate/unchanged), <span class="emphasis">Availability</span> (systems stay up and accessible).</p>
            <p>Example: For tw¬°st3d_¬°nk Academy ‚Äì Confidentiality protects learner data; Integrity ensures course content isn't tampered; Availability keeps the site online for your escape route.</p>
            <!-- Embed image here if we add <img src="cia-triad.jpg" alt="CIA Triad Diagram"> -->
        </div>
        <div class="section">
            <h3>Threat Modeling: Real-World Application</h3>
            <p>Think like an attacker: What could go wrong? Who wants in? Use our academy as case study ‚Äì threats like domain hijacking or content defacement.</p>
            <p>Crown Jewels: Domain (twist3dink.xyz), Hosting (GitHub), Content (lessons), Identity (your story), Reputation (trust as a healer).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="section">
            <h3>Prioritization Exercise</h3>
            <p>You ranked: Integrity > Confidentiality > Availability. Reasoning: Tampered content could mislead learners healing from trauma ‚Äì worse than downtime or leaks.</p>
            <p>Defense-in-Depth: Layers like MFA, backups, monitoring ‚Äì protect the core first, like rebuilding self-trust layer by layer.</p>
            <p>Incident Response Basics: Detect, contain, recover, learn. When things go wrong, don't dissociate ‚Äì face it, fix it.</p>
        </div>
        
        ‚úÖ <h2>Success Criteria</h2>
